From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Gwan-gyeong Mun <gwan-gyeong.mun@intel.com>
Date: Thu, 9 May 2024 11:32:51 +0300
Subject: drm/xe/eudebug/xe3p: Pagefault exception debugging
 support

Xe3p is the first platform generation introducing the pagefault memory
exception debugging feature. This feature optionally raises a software
exception through the EU thread (more precisely, GAM) if a memory
access made by a EU kernel results in an unhandled page fault.
This replaces the existing behavior where a catastrophic error is raised
when an unhandled page fault is encountered, normally resulting
in an engine reset.

The Pagefault exception debugging feature can be enabled with the
DRM_XE_EXEC_QUEUE_SET_PROPERTY_EUDEBUG extension of the
DRM_IOCTL_XE_EXEC_QUEUE_CREATE ioctl.
And the extension property value requires to set with
DRM_XE_EXEC_QUEUE_EUDEBUG_FLAG_ENABLE and
DRM_XE_EXEC_QUEUE_EUDEBUG_FLAG_PAGEFAULT_ENABLE.

If a Pagefault exception raised from the EU thread, the SIP
(System Routine) program in the EU thread handles the exception and calls
the sync.host instruction. When the sync.host of EU thread instruction is
called, the GuC sends XE_GUC_ACTION_NOTIFY_EU_KERNEL_DEBUG_EVENT to the
KMD, the same as the EU breakpoint flow. Therefore, when a Pagefault
exception raises from the EU, the KMD sends the
DRM_XE_EUDEBUG_EVENT_EU_STOP event to the UMD, the same as the breakpoint
flow handling. (The KMD does not distinguish between pagefault exception
and breakpoint cases.)

v2: lrc_create adaptation (Mika)

v3: adapted to eudebug v3 (Maciej)

